<text>A hidden gem in South Coast Plaza! The food and service was excellent. They have live music every night as well as cooking classes and theme nights. Can't wait to go back!!</text><Response>None< /Response><pictures>None</pictures><gmapID>0x80dcdf2f80af9bfb:0x2d0b31fc1fa593de< /gmapID>< Date>
1558063719016< /Date>
<rating>5< /rating><Name>Carmen Mead</Name>< userid>
107342490006600686021<//userid>
</record></dataset><record>
< Text>
When my significant other wanted to come here for his birthday lunch, it was an unexpected delight. I love Italian food and people very much, having spent eight years with an Italian family before. My significant other's father goes to Italy every year and loves to spend time in Como. Few restaurants in the United States that we've been to have felt Italian, and this was one of them.

When you come here, nearly entire shopping center scene disappears from your senses. The interior cleverly uses a more honeyed wood color from floor-to-ceiling, creating a more cocooned, relaxed setting. The ingredients used here are fresh and fabulous. It is essentially what food should be but in the United States a lot of things are overly processed and our agricultural industrial complex farming makes for produce lacking in flavor.

I was pleasantly surprised by the tomato sauce tasting just like what I had remembered of a freshly made tomato sauce according to a Nonna's recipe. I hadn't tasted this in almost a decade.

We had spaghetti con polpette and pizza with prosciutto and arugula. The crust, pasta, and bread all had great texture and taste. I  loved the bitter bite of the arugula. Imported cheeses were delectable. The meat in the polpette was fresh, the polpette were dense and generous in portion. Pasta was undoubtedly al dente. I love, love, love tomatoes, olive oil, and balsamic vinegar. The olive oil and balsamic vinegar had a beautiful, ripe fruity taste.

The European Union bans an artificial growth hormone that is used a lot in American dairy (rBST, synthesized from a strain of e coli) which some people have adverse reactions to. These reactions can be in creases of inflammation in the body, adrenal and thyroid problems, cystic acne related to hormonal problems, and migraines. My significant other and I have these health issues when we eat dairy with rBST but we had none of these reactions to the foods that we ate at this restaurant.

Speaking of Nonna's, I was curious about  a photo of a chocolate cake and a flourless chocolate cake described as a torta della nonna dessert menu. A torta della nonna is a lemony custard tart, isn't it?

We had a white chocolate, berry, pistachio, and cream cake that was utterly delectable. One of the best things we've ever eaten.

The people who work here are very attentive and congenial. We appreciate their warmth and hospitality very much. We'd love to keep coming back.

And, their selection of music is primo.< /Text>
<Time>1581563857330<//Time><Gmap_id>0x80dcdf2f80af9bfb:0x2d0b31fc1fa593de<//Gmap_id>< Name>
Emma Bennett<//Name>

<Pics>None</Pics>< Text>
This used to be one of my favorite restaurants but the last few times have been really bad. I ordered a pizza which came out burned. When I pointed it out I got a BS response saying "well its a little overcooked but do you really want another one"? YES I DO!! I am not paying for lousy food, I can get that anywhere. On my next visit I ordered a glass of chardonnay and it came with a very small pour. I asked if they thought it was a little small and got a very curt response that it was their standard. I have eaten there many, many times and this pour was NOT their standard. Sorry but it is off my list now. Too many better choices.<//Text>

< Review>
I was here for an early dinner (the time slot in which most people have happy hour).  I only had 30 minutes for dinner before volunteer training.  I asked Kelly (if I remember the server's name correctly) if the Pollo alla Birra took a long time to prepare since I had a limited amount of time.  He told me that it would take 10 minutes.  Awesome!

In 10 minutes, I had a plate of subtly seasoned (the taste of lemon was dominant for those who like hints of lemon).  The broccoli had a garlic seasoning which was good.  I loved the asiago mashed potatoes.  It's not often a restaurant puts asiago in their mashed potatoes but it's an excellent idea.

In terms of service, I didn't have to wait  for the bill or the takeout box (the portions are generous).  The coffee I ordered towards the end of the meal were put in a to go coffee cup.  2 questions: Was my server psychic?  This type of upscale restaurant has to go coffee cups?!

Needless to say, this has been one of the most magical, seamless restaurant experiences I've ever had and I dine out a lot.  The next time I'm in town, I'm coming back to try other dishes!< /Review>

Adam patiently explains the work needed, and has taken the time to walk us through the new systems. <Review>My wife and I bought a classic 40+ year old RV on EBay, hoping to use it as a mobile office. The photos were beautiful and we bought it "as is" from Michigan, over 2,000 miles away, without an inspection.

We peeled back the vintage shag rug to do a simple carpet replacement and discovered that the wood floor and the overhead sleeping area were rotten with mold and wood decay from years of hidden water leaks. We soon had a long list of problems with plumbing, electricity, woodwork, appliances, cabinets, etc.

I checked out Avalon RV Restoration and liked the owner and the crew. They seem to love the restoration of classic trailers and do excellent work. They have about a dozen vintage trailers on the lot, mostly Airstreams, being restored or in line for restoration. I waited eight weeks for a slot.
Their prices are fair and the quality of work is superb. From custom cabinetry to ingenious electrical upgrades, you couldn't ask for more. Thanks to Avalon, we now have a beautiful wood interior, warm low-amp LED lighting, upgraded heater, modern upgraded converter and inverter, re-worked plumbing, new rooftop sealant, a first-rate battery bank, and high-output solar panels. They flood-tested the clear, gray, and black water tanks, and pressure tested the entire RV for leaks. The floor is actually stronger and better than new, with new frame welding and foam insulation sandwiched between marine plywood--no squeaks, no spongy spots, and finished with understated Marmoleum.

Avalon saved our vintage RV from the junk heap and kept a beautifully restored work of art on the road.<//Review>< Time>

<resp>None<//resp><gmap_id>0x80856e7c0be8a307:0x6aa65d6526ef540e</gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<Review>I took my van into Adam to correct wiring problems on an install done by a different RV repair shop in Redwood City, V&V Bros.  V&V installed my 3 160W Renolgy panels on the roof to a Kodiak 1500W llithium generator, but it never charged after they installed it. I took it back 2 times to check the wiring but they blamed in first on the battery, and then said 2 of the panels weren't working.

I took it to Adam at Avalon for a second opinion before I sent the solar panels back for a refund. He found all 3 panels were working perfectly. The problem was the faulty wiring job. Some of the MC4 connectors on the roof were hooked up male to female and some female to female. The biggest problem was the splice where the two cables came through the gland into the van. They were spliced incorrectly in reverse polarity. The Zodiak has an automatic shut off if it detects reverse polarity so that's why it wasn't charging. I appreciate the thoroughness of Adam's work in detecting this flaw.  After he rewired the splice, the system has been working perfectly. It went from 10.88 A to full charge by the time I'd driven home. Since then I've gotten up to almost 13A daily. It's nice to have a system that works!

In addition to his patience in detecting these flaws, Adam also spent some time on the phone with a person on the Zodiak tech team who read questions and answers from a script. It was very frustrating to get a straight answer out of customer service, and at one point, I tried to grab the phone to unload my frustratrion on the tech person, but Adam moved it just in time and continued patiently to ask the questions he needed the answers to in order to proceed. A life lession there for me--restrain anger with customer service until you get what you need. Ha!

Adam was very knowledgeable about solar, enjoys talking about solar, and seems like a very kind person. The money I was charged for Adam's work was worth every penney and I would recommend him wholeheartedly.</Review>< response>

<Rate>5<//Rate><Review>I saw Dr. Jafari for acne scars on my face (mostly on cheeks and some on forehead) and as per her recommendations, did 3 session of fractional CO2 laser. Both my nurses were excellent as I truly enjoyed the experience. As for the treatment, there wasn't much discomfort with numbing and I experienced some redness and mild swelling after the lasers (more after the first one, I guess my skin got used and adjusted to it). . All instructions were pretty clear and easy to follow. There were 2 creams to apply, one right after the treatment to keep the skin protected and the other one before and between the treatments to reduce skin darkening for better results. I also had to wash my face gently over the first few days. Overall not that bad. Now the great part: I am glad to report that my scars are noticeably better after completing the 3 sessions. They are not completely gone (and I didn't really expected that and Dr. Jafari also told me about it ahead of time), but I am happy with the improvements so far and will most likely try a few more sessions later on. Dr. Jafari also recommended I do Bellafill for a few larger scars and that's also my plan once I am done with the lasers since the laser seems to be working good for me. < Review>
I have done Ultherapy at Dr. Jafari's office for my eyebrows, lower face/jawline and neck all with very good results. My initial concern was fine lines around the eyes and some loose skin on the neck but as I consulted Dr. she indicated that I can be a good candidate for Ultherapy and so I decided to do more areas and am so happy that I did. Ultherapy is a pretty thorough and targeted treatment that focuses on stimulating collagen so it's supposed to work gradually with lasting results and I can attest to that so far. I had the treatment a little over 9 months ago and it took me around 8-9 weeks to start noticing first results (best seen in serial pictures) in my eyebrows and crows feet. The jawline and neck were a bit behind but I could see clear improvements in about 3 months and I think I got to the peak at around 6 months. I guess the key is to remain patient since it's your own body that is working to make the new collagen and if you give it the time in needs, I'm sure you won't be disappointed. Dr. Jafari and her nurses at Amoderm are very nice and supportive and I always felt well taken care of working with them. Great experience!< /Review>

< review>
Did my 3rd laser for acne scars on my face 2 months ago and I can give an accurate account now. I have been suffering from scars mostly on my cheeks since teenage years and tried many creams to no avail so I decided to go for the laser treatment. Dr. Jafar recommended 3 sessions of fractional CO2 laser to start. I did use the prep cream for around 2 weeks to get my skin ready for laser and did the treatment after numbing cream (provided by the office). I can tell that the laser was pretty intensive and I had noticeable redness for the next few days. I followed the instructions closely with the healing cream and soaks, etc and was careful not to pull at my skin. As my skin healed and a couple of weeks passed I could see some improvements which encouraged me to continue with the remaining 2 sessions and I am glad I did as my skin got better after each round. I highly recommend going for a couple of rounds as 1 session is usually not enough. Also following the clinic instructions after each laser session is critical to make sure healing is quick and complete. Based on my experience I can recommend fractional CO2 laser for acne scars and I do recommend Amoderm as a great clinic to get this treatment.< /review>

<user>104467298926050633193<//user><Pics>None< /Pics>< Text>
Very pleased with the results of my Bellafill injection by Dr. Jafari at AModerm. I had done microneedling with PRP there before (and it really helped with tone and texture of my skin) but I was looking for a long-term solution to add some volume to my relatively receding chin and also to make my jaw lines more defined and wasn't ready for surgery so I went to see Dr. Jafari and I am so happy. She recommended Voluma and Bellafill and I opted for the 2nd option hoping that it will last longer. Did the allergy test (which came negative) and then she injected one syringe of Bellafill to my chin and 3 more for the jawlines. The treatment was ok and not much painful. Had no bruising but a bit of welling which went away after a few days (no icing needed). While I was happy to see the initial lift, the collagen stimulation part of the filler gave it a much better boost and after almost 4 months, I am even happier with the results (best appreciated when compared with my previous pictures since Dr. Jafari's wok is really natural and she does her best to make sure it "fits" the face as opposed to standing out). I am scheduled to see her again this month to see if she recommend more Bellafill injections, but so far I am very happy.< /Text>

I went to see Dr. J for Kybella after doing lots of research and she confirmed that I was a good candidate and recommend two rounds of injection with 2 and 1 vials. I had some swelling the first time but not much in the second time. The double chin is reduced by maybe 30-40% which is good enough for me and the skin definitely feels firmer over the treated area which is big bonus. So far no numbness or other issues, so keeping my fingers crossed!<//review>

<text>I visited Dr. Jafari last year when I did a consult to see what treatments are available to contour my jawline and make it firmed and help with the moderate double chin I had for many years. Dr. Jafari suggested Kybella and recommended that I do 3 rounds of injection with a total 6 vials. I followed her recommendation and didn‚Äôt have much issue other than a bit of swelling after each injection which lasted for 1-2 days and went away. The good news is that Kybella worked very well and after doing the 3rd round and waiting for a few months to make sure it‚Äôs done its magic, I am glad to say that the double chin is significantly less and almost 30-40% gone. During this time I maintained the same weight so I can tell for sure that the Kybella has worked for me, but for anyone considering it, please be patient and follow your doctor‚Äôs recommendation since almost everyone needs to complete the 2-3 rounds of injection to see good results. I really enjoy my new slimmer profile and the firmer jaw line and recommend this treatment and this wonderful doctor!<//text>< time>

I have a recessed chin which affected my face in very unpleasant way and made my neck look short. I wasn‚Äôt ready for surgery and didn‚Äôt want to do chin implants so I was happy to learn that it can be fixed with filler and after lots of research, saw Dr. Jafari. She did chin augmentation with Voluma and was able to reshape my chin and add a nice prominence which is a lot more in line with my face and neck and I can‚Äôt believe how much positive difference this relatively simple procedure has made. The whole visit took around 30 minutes (plus an initial consult I had done before) I was back to work right after the injection with not swelling or other issues. Voluma is more expensive but I think it‚Äôs well worth the price as it lasts longer and holds its shape better. Following the chin filler, I also did my lips with Voluma and also did Botox on mu frown lines and crow‚Äôs feet with Dr. Jafari. Dr. Jafari is very nice and attentive and I felt very comfortable being treated by her.< /Text>

I visited Dr. Jafari last year when I did a consult to see what treatments are available to contour my jawline and make it firmed and help with the moderate double chin I had for many years. <date>1514331364146</date><Rating>2<//Rating>< review>
I have had multiple laser hair removal sessions at Amoderm. If you really want to go there let me give you the scoop:

1) If they offer you a "package" deal (and they will), don't take it! Their package deal worked out to about $200 a session. My sessions would last about 15 minutes.

If you look at their pricing, they claim you can buy a half hour for $150. That means I paid almost double the price for my first few sessions. Whoops! Shame on me I guess.

2) Inconsistent staff roster and quality. Some of their techs are good, some aren't. This will really change the results of your session, and how much they get done. I have had really good work and I have had sessions where they obviously missed spots. They seem to have a hard time keeping the good people. Hmmmmm....

3) If they burn you don't expect much from them. I now have a 1.5 inch scar on my back where a tech hit my tattoo with the laser (which also obliterated part of the tattoo BTW). Their response? Bummer for you. Here's some cream that will make the scar go away (It didn't).

4) If you still really want to buy their services I recommend you set a timer at the start of your session! What finally broke me as a customer was when I bought an hour of hair removal and got 40 minutes. Pretty sneaky stuff.

I have a hard time believing all these 5 star reviews. In my experience, they are pretty mediocre to poor in every aspect of their business. I hope this review is helpful and you can avoid some of the pitfalls that I encountered when purchasing their services.

So here's an update: Shortly after I posted this review someone called me and offered a free session to compensate me for my troubles. Thanks, but no thanks. This isn't about the money. I want other people to know what happened and to be able to defend themselves from your business practices. You have taken me for a fool. I'm sure you do it to other clients and then buy them off if they complain publicly. Not me. This review stays up.

I have also included a picture to show you what it looks like when they miss spots doing hair removal. You can see how the hair on my abdomin has grown bacvk in with a leopard pattern. Thanks Amoderm!< /review>

<text>I heard about Amoderm from a friend and after doing some research about them online, decided to take the plunge and commit myself to the long drive from Los Angeles to OC. It wasn't just the long drive, but i was mainly nervous as it was my first time trying a cosmetic doctor. I have had some lines and wrinkles on my forehead and around eyes that were starting to get pretty noticeable and also didn't like the deepening lines running up around my mouth. I called Amoderm first and spoke with a lady who explained everything in detail. I told her I wasn't sure what I needed and what was best for me, and she reassured me that Dr. Jafari always does a detailed consultation and explains things that can be done and then I could decide if I wanted to do any of the treatments she suggested. Upon my arrival to the clinic, I was happy to see that the clinic was very nice and clean (with tons of parking which is a huge plus for anyone coming from LA!). The front ladies greeted me with big smiles and gave me their forms to fill and within minutes, I was seen by Dr. Jafari. Let me just tell you that Dr. Jafari is the sweetest and nicest doctor I've seen in my life! She is very friendly and all my stress and concerns disappeared within seconds as she started to talk with me and discuss the reason I was there and what was bothering me. She listened very carefully and as we talked, reviewed my pictures and areas that could use some help. She also reviewed tons of pictures from her other patients and things that she had done for them, and it was easy to see that she knew exactly what she was talking about. At the end, I decided to do some botox for my forehead and between eyebrows and some juvederm for my face (cheeks and around the mouth) and it was much easier that I thought!! She used this long needle to do the injections under the skin as she moved it around without having to poke the skin many times. It was completely pain-free, but I had to say it was a weird feeling having the needles moving under your skin! But no pain, so no complaints! We were done in no time and she gave me a lecture on things to do and not to do and what to expect after the shots and I was on my way. Now a couple of weeks has passed and I can't just believe the positive transformation this whole thing has made to my life! I no longer have to suffer from the tired and down look I used to have and I enjoy all the compliments I get from others - friends, family, coworkers and customers - on how energetic and refreshed I look. I always chuckle a bit as I can see that they can't really say what I have done but they just see that something is different in a good way, and that's really what I was hoping for to have natural results. Discovering Amoderm and Dr. Jaafari was one of the best things that happened to me, and I will gladly make the long drive anytime to go back and see her. Stop your search and call them if you are looking for an honest, nice, experienced and skilled cosmetic doctor and you won't regret it!<//text><pictures>None< /pictures>< Response>

<pics>None</pics><review>Should allow bikes or at least have bike racks so those of us who go there often and like to find a private place to spend the day to sit and write don't have to haul a bunch of stuff up that steep hill. It's hard to carry something to eat and drink plus writing necessities plus a jacket or sweatshirt plus required medications plus something to sit on plus phone and backup battery pack plus whatever else is needed for someone with major health issues to be able to spend several hours out in nature. At the very least bike racks would help so bikes don't have to just be left off to the side at the bottom of the trail where anyone can see it and steal it if they wanted. At least then the back and forth trips to check on the bike with a load of stuff could be avoided. Being able to bring the bike would be ideal so the bike would be able to carry the load and trips to check on the bike wouldn't be necessary and writing would be easier without interruptions and distractions.< /review></record></dataset><record>

<Name>Joe G</Name><gmap_id>0x8085ac11a7b2122f:0x978d3febc13992c0</gmap_id><response>None< /response><date>1462158781489</date><review>The Sonoma Overlook trail is an easy hike, even with a chronic illness. Great views. Lots of people wearing spandex tights. Flowers and places to sit. Trail is in partial shade. I was told the trail was 1 to 1.5 miles to the top. The trail is not steep, but it is somewhat rocky and uneven so wear decent shoes, but even then I saw someone in sandals walk up. Bring water because there is none on the trail Beware of ticks, they carry Lyme disease and the trail sign warns of this.</review></record>

This is one of the top parks in Orange County! I used to walk over to Panorama Park all the time when I was little. It‚Äôs nestled in the heart of Fullerton, perched on top of a hill granting access to the beautiful endless view. 4</Rating>
<text>I recently added this bookmark and was eager to check it out. It's easily accessible via the Summit House parking lot; just follow the signs as you near the Coyote Hills golf course!

Eye candy all around!! Not the type you're probably thinking of... but abundant, nonetheless!  Bunnies, butterflies, squirrels, dragonflies, and oodles of flowers, trees & flowering bushes!  And the views from up top *gasp* .... I can't wait to return for an evening excursion and take in the view of the city lights below!!

The terrain varies along the path from paved trail,  to horse trail, dirt & rocks, grass & mulch.... Definitely not a monotonous trek!  Just be sure to stay on the trails and watch the signs... There is private property belonging to the nearby golf course and they want you to STAY OUT/OFF!

All types are attracted here... young, old, hikers, joggers, bicyclists, photographers, me.... Be sure your phone has a full charge because you will snap more photos than expected.... Other than selfies! :P</text><user>116050763823303540634< /user>< user_name>

<Resp>None<//Resp>< text>
Solid place to hike and always clean. Just a short uphill walk with amazing views. Sits up on the backside of coyote hills golf club. Once on top you can see some spectacular views stretching from south Newport to the city of L.A. and to the east from big bear to Santiago peak covering the LA. Basin. Well worth it. Make some memories and take in the beauty just make sure to leave around Dusk or you will be jumping the fence to get out. Enjoy my friends. One love and clean up after yourself.< /text>
<time>1561793902426< /time><Name>Ray Berry</Name><pics>None<//pics><gmapID>0x80dcd5bcb8b1e5af:0x6744633de5ddac3d</gmapID><userid>118310821840658669233</userid><Rate>5< /Rate></record></dataset><record>

< review>
A nice, safe hike! The top part is really pretty, but a majority of it is just along the roads. It's accessible via the events center parking, but sometimes the golfers will put the chain with the locks around the entrance to make it seem like it's closed. It is unlocked though! For me this is a very accessible, safe, good workout. I hike it in about an hour, but that rate definitely gets my heart beating fast.< /review>

<Gmap_id>0x808fec6b4382bc37:0xecc19ab34a2f3ed1</Gmap_id><user>100898209470161521815</user>< review>
Took my 88 Ford Bronco 2 to Schuck's Transmission a few weeks ago after AAMCO botched a rebuild in 2012. Jeff and his team were very courteous. Jeff took the time to hear me out about the 2-3 shift flare and how I had tried the band adjustment and shift modulator replacement with no improvement before I decided to bring it in for professional repair. Jeff was honest with me about the amount of work it would need. After the repairs, I was able to get a box of the parts that were replaced. While the transmission was being rebuilt, they also replaced the flywheel due to some broken teeth. I inspected their work afterwards and was very pleased to the attention to detail. The shift adjustment nuts on this A4LD are prone to loosening so I saw that Jeff's team had put some gasket on thise after adjustment.

Lesson learned, don't take your transmission to AAMCO for a cheap rebuild. Schuck's has been a good experience and Jeff was willing to take my calls and answer any questions I had. He even provided me with the manuals for the shift kit they installed to improve the shifting after rebuild. I also saw the aftermath of the botched rebuild in the worn bands and worn out center support that was replaced.

I can rest easy now that Schuck's transmission did the job right.<//review>

< review>
300% MARKUP on parts used during repair and a THREE WEEK turnaround time? What an embarrassment of a shop. I've waited several months to write this review so that I could evaluate the work done on my automobile. With that said, I highly recommend that you take your automobile elsewhere. It's wise to look outside of the tri-valley area, because the local shops here will rip you off. My classic car was returned to me in an arguably worse condition. It certainly drives a lot worse than when I handed it over to Robert--horrible vibrations. He then had the audacity to justify mark-ups on parts that were ordered from a manufacturer's website (see the attached image). Furthermore, I was never asked which replacement parts I wanted installed on my vehicle. The shop only called me to update the process a single time; I initiated almost all communication during this drawn out process. The total cost was about $500 over-budget (see the attached picture of the poorly written ticket). I don't even think I should make a warranty claim with Schuck's... I'd hate to let my car go for another two months. If you must go to a local shop, go to Broadway motors located on the same block as Schuck's. Do not get scammed here. My first thought was the pilot light was out and I needed to re-light it. It worked but it went out a few minutes later. I noticed the light flashing and checked the code on the front panel. According to the number of flashes, the burner assembly needed to be replaced. Colepepper Plumbing immediately came to mind because of the ad I hear on the radio all the time. Sorry but it's so annoying that it stuck in my head. Anyway, I called and Alex came out the next day. He assessed the situation, and agreed the burner needed to be replacement. < text>
I reached out to Colepepper plumbing to receive a bid for some repairs that were listed on a home inspection report for a home my wife and I are trying to buy on a Saturday. I was told that they could for sure assist me, and have a plumber out between 10-2 on Sunday, and they would call about 30 min before they arrived. We reached out to our agent so the sellers could be ready as well.

I called at 11 on the day of the appointment to confirm it. I was told yes we were confirmed it would be another hour.

I called at 12:30 to follow up as it had been over an hour. I was told that they had a lot of calls and I was next.

I called at 1:30 again to see what the ETA was, as we were trying to coordinate this with the owners. I was told I was next and they would be arriving shortly.

Anyways, 4pm arrives, 2 hours outside of their four hour window. And they say they should have someone over in another hour or so... we needed to reschedule for Monday.

Monday arrives, the plumber arrives to the home before I do, and does not call. Walks through the home with the seller, then leaves.

I call the office to have the plumber return, and provided a copy of the inspection report outlining the multiple issues that arose, and requested a bid on the items. The plumber says okay, we'll take this to the office and send it back to you later today.

Monday evening, no bid. I call the office to request the bid, and they send over a blank estimate stating everything is in working order, and addressing none of the issues on the report provided. I reply with a copy of the report again and request they update to reflect the items, and call back in to request it. They say they will send it right away.

Tuesday - still no bid. Was sent another bid for the cost of an expansion tank... not listed anywhere on my request. I've been calling the office over and over just to be told that they need to reach out to someone else and get back to me.

Every time I call in they are unapologetic, and offer nothing in the way of timelines on this issue to be corrected.</text>

<Rate>1</Rate><review>I have a 50 year-ish old  home in San Diego with old pipes and a history of backed up plumbing.  Several companies have been out over the years, however, it  has not been mentioned to replace or reline the pipes.  Continual clearing, jetting of the lines finally came down to a permanent solution.  My tenant called Colepepper out.  The invoice said they descaled the line [it is questionable that this was done], camera'd it, dug and replaced about 5' of pipe, then made recommendations.  They also pulled a toilet and reset it.  The bill was $1700.  [The line had already been jetted about 2-3 months previous].   They sent over an estimate detailing 5 options for a permanent solution ranging from $20,000 to $65,000.  The option they recommended most was the 4th most expensive at $36,000.  This was to reline the major portion of the drain line.This is a lot of money, so I called out some other people for estimates.  3 subsequent reputable companies each quoted about the same amount and the same work for about 25% what Colepepper bid.  So my obvious choice is not Colepepper.  The office rang me discuss payment for work done and asked what bids I had gotten from other companies.  I told them and was then asked if Colepepper would meet those bids would I work with them?  I said absolutely not.  I am not going to work with a company who drops their price from $40,000 to $10,000.  Seriously?  After reading numerous online reviews they seem to be split.  For the most part customers say their work was great and fast, but then there are numerous 1 star reviews or price gouging.  My husband is a contractor, so I am well aware of the tactics some contractors use.  It is altogether possible for 2 highly respected and competent contractors, known for honesty and integrity to have bids where one may be double what the other was.  Many things come into play.  A small company that doesn't have a lot of office and marketing overhead may charge a lot less but do a bang-up job.  The larger company has marketing, payroll, employee benefits, and on down the line to cover so they have to charge more.  But not 4 times more.
Beware.</review><Pics>None< /Pics><resp>{'time': 1605627065694, 'text': "You are comparing apples and oranges. Our scope of work included many things the other companies did not. ‚ÄúThat drain a clogged before and snaking from the roof has been the only thing to work‚Äù I said

‚ÄúIt will cost around $3200 to repair the pipe under the house‚Äù said the tech.

‚ÄúAnd can you snake the roof vent?‚Äù I asked

‚ÄúIt will cost $380 to go into the roof and snake the vent‚Äù the tech said

Now, the drain is still clogged, the toilet is off the floor which is fine I removed it for them, and I am out $71.

<Text>Our main water line broke, sending water up through the concrete slab near our front porch and flooding our downstairs bath, requiring the water service to be shut off.

Leo from Colepepper came out, gave me a bid, and worked with me to match the price, etc., from another quote. We agreed on details, and Leo said he'd be there the next day.

Leo arrived the next day, and started immediately digging. After some time, Jose showed up, and started working as well.

All work was completed, and a couple minor issues were taken care of right away after my inspection of the work. This included a 16" trench dug in the front yard, where we have rocks, landscape fabric, and sprinklers; removing the concrete directly in front of the stairs at the entry (!); new copper pipe from the street to the garage (replacing the old polybutalene); new valves at the street, in the garage, plus a water bib; replacing the concrete in front of the porch, and restoring the front yard including new fabric, etc.

Jose did a fine job with the concrete. I was worried about this, since it is directly in front of the main entry (see photo). It looks great.

< text>
I had what appeared to be a leak from my hot water heater in my condo this past weekend.  I called another plumbing company Saturday and got scammed.  They replaced supply lines at a cost of $225.00 confident the issue was resolved.  It was not.  The owner came out the following day perplexed and very unsure of himself stating to accurately diagnose he had to tear down my walls to expose all the pipes to determine it.  This left me uneasy and skeptical.  I told him I needed the night to sleep on it.  Monday morning decided best to get a second opinion from a company with greater expertise at detecting leaks.  I called Colepepper Plumbing explaining my situation.  They offered to come out and give me a free estimate and within an hour Joshua arrived.  He immediately sensed my hesitation due to my previous experience and very quickly gained my trust by taking extra time confidently, kindly explaining in detail what needed to be done along with the cost (which did not involve tearing down my walls!).  In less than 1 hour he found the problem which had nothing to do with my condo at all !!  The neighbor's hot water heater had burst leaking into the exterior and interior of my unit causing fairly extensive damage.  He also took pictures and wrote a detailed receipt for my documentation in moving forward to gain reimbursement.  Then took it a step further to advise me of how to get my money back from the past plumber.  Using his words would you know I received a full refund in 45 minutes !!  I am in the customer service industry myself and Colepepper  Plumbing is at the top in this department.  I would refer them to anyone and everyone.  They will be the sole company I will go to for all my future plumbing needs.  They may be a bit more pricey but you get what you pay for !!  This is a smaller company that is efficient, courteous, clean, believe you matter and truly care about who you are.  Thank You Joshua & Mitch for everything !!</text>

I had a homeowners' policy with First American (terrible company) and they contracted with A-Z Appliances which is greatly undermanned in the call center.  My gas line leaked on our dryer and SDG&E had to come out to shut it off or the home would have gone up in flames.  I immediately filed with First American and they gave me the contractor to take care of it. They scheduled on a Friday.  No show.  Then I was assured they'd be there on Saturday.  Again, no show.  Then A-Z promised they'd be there on Monday. You guessed it: no show.  After waiting 20 minutes on hold I finally got through to the only one in the call center - Adam - who is overworked and a very nice man - but management does not communicate with him.  He said he'd talk to the manager (whoever that is) and get back to me.  He called me back and said since the dryer is okay First American would not cover a new flex gasline and duct for the dryer.  I had seen an ad in the San Diego Union-Tribune and called and Mitch, the owner, answered and was terrific. I can't emphasize the professionalism and thoroughness enough.  I strongly recommend if you need a plumber or for anything electrical or gas wise, you will be greatly satisfied with Colepepper Plumbing.  My wife and I give them 5 enthusiastic stars.</Review>
